{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3688231,"name":null,"username":"4D4850","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/4/e274bd/{size}.png","created_at":"2025-07-24T00:12:01.167Z","cooked":"<p>I’m one of the programmers for Team STEAM, and I’ve been working on switching us from Limelight to Photonvision for us to use at CowTown and for next year. I’ve been working on implementing pose estimation, but the roborio runs out of memory after a short amount of time if the code creates an AprilTagFieldLayout.</p>
<p>We have a meeting tomorrow, and while I at least want to try not bothering with making an AprilTagFieldLayout and just try using the result from<br>
AprilTagFieldLayout.loadField directly, I figured it would be wise to ask for any other solutions.</p>
<p>The code specifically returned either a java memory allocation error, something along the lines of “what(): std::bad_alloc”, or both.</p>
<p>I don’t know the specific Roborio we have on our robot.</p>
<p>Code for pose estimation, with commented out or entirely unrelated code removed:</p>
<pre data-code-wrap="java"><code class="lang-java">public class EstimatorSubsystem extends SubsystemBase {
  private VisionSubsystem m_vision;
  private PhotonPoseEstimator estimator;
  private Optional&lt;EstimatedRobotPose&gt; estimatePose;
  Drive m_drive;
  Pose2d robotPose;
  public static final Matrix&lt;N3, N1&gt; robotPoseStdDev = new Matrix&lt;N3, N1&gt;(Nat.N3(), Nat.N1());
  // AprilTagFieldLayout aprilTagFieldLayout = AprilTagFieldLayout.loadField(AprilTagFields.kDefaultField);
  // If the above line of code isn't commented out, the roborio crashes
  Optional&lt;PhotonPipelineResult&gt; latestResult;
  public EstimatorSubsystem(Drive drive, VisionSubsystem vision) {
    m_drive = drive;
    // estimator = new PhotonPoseEstimator(aprilTagFieldLayout, PoseStrategy.MULTI_TAG_PNP_ON_COPROCESSOR, Constants.Vision.robotToCam);
    m_vision = vision;
    robotPoseStdDev.set(0, 0, Constants.Vision.robotPoseStdDev[0]);
    robotPoseStdDev.set(1, 0, Constants.Vision.robotPoseStdDev[1]);
    robotPoseStdDev.set(2, 0, Constants.Vision.robotPoseStdDev[2]);
  }
</code></pre>
